SIMPLE: marigold
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Marigold
<hw>Mar"i*gold</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mary</ets> +
<ets>gold</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A name for several plants
with golden yellow blossoms, especially the <spn>Calendula
officinalis</spn> (see <er>Calendula</er>), and the cultivated species
of <gen>Tagetes</gen>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ There are several yellow-flowered plants of different
genera bearing this name; as, the <stype>African marigold</stype>
<it>or</it> <stype>French marigold</stype> of the genus
<gen>Tagetes</gen>, of which several species and many varieties are
found in gardens. They are mostly strong-smelling herbs from South
America and Mexico: <stype>bur marigold</stype>, of the genus
<gen>Bidens</gen>; <stype>corn marigold</stype>, of the genus
<gen>Chrysanthemum</gen> (<spn>Chrysanthemum segetum</spn>, a pest in
the cornfields of Italy); <stype>fig marigold</stype>, of the genus
<gen>Mesembryanthemum</gen>; <stype>marsh marigold</stype>, of the genus
<gen>Caltha</gen> (<spn>Caltha palustris</spn>), commonly known in
America as the <stype>cowslip</stype>. See <er>Marsh
Marigold</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marigold window</b></col>. <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <cd>See
<cref>Rose window</cref>, under <er>Rose</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marijuana</ent>⟦br⟧
